<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="158" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,778,805,1838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,305,1498,1524]" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Remarks.</emphasis>
Intheoriginaldescriptionof 
<taxonomicName authority=", Zhang &amp; Chen" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Chen" class="Branchiopoda" family="Branchiopoda (awaiting allocation)" genus="Halysestheria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Branchiopoda (awaiting allocation)" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[615,771,1498,1524]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Halysestheria</emphasis>
, Zhang &amp; Chen
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[333,355,1534,1559]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, W. T. &amp; Chen, P. J. &amp; Shen, Y. B." box="[366,586,1533,1560]" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" refId="ref5922" refString="Zhang, W. T., Chen, P. J. &amp; Shen, Y. B. (1976) Fossil Conchostraca of China. Science Press, Beijing, 325 pp., 138 pls. [In Chinese]." type="book" year="1976">
Zhang 
<emphasis box="[450,503,1533,1559]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">et al</emphasis>
., 1976
</bibRefCitation>
) overlooked the puncta on growth bands and the serration along the lower margins of growth lines, which were first seen by Li (2005) in specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chang, 1957)" baseAuthorityName="Chang" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[315,677,1637,1664]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Branchiopoda (awaiting allocation)" genus="Halysestheria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Branchiopoda (awaiting allocation)" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yui">
<emphasis box="[315,511,1637,1663]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Halysestheria yui</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chang, W. T." box="[525,669,1637,1664]" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" pagination="479 - 502" refId="ref4060" refString="Chang, W. T. (1957) Fossil Conchostraca from the Nenjiang Shale, NW Heilongjiang. Acta Palaeontologica Sinica, 5, 479 - 502. 6 pls." type="book chapter" year="1957">Chang, 1957</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Upper Cretaceous Taipinglinchang Formation along the 
<collectingRegion box="[136,282,1706,1732]" country="China" name="Heilongjiang" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Heilongjiang</collectingRegion>
river in northern 
<collectingRegion box="[510,774,1706,1732]" country="China" name="Heilongjiang" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Heilongjiang Province</collectingRegion>
. These features were also discovered in specimens from the First Member of the Upper Cretaceous Nenjiang Formation in Yaojia, 
<collectingRegion box="[373,529,1811,1837]" country="China" name="Jilin" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">Jilin Province</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Li, G. &amp; Wan, X. Q. &amp; Batten, D. J. &amp; Bengtson, P. &amp; Xi, D. P. &amp; Wang, P. J." box="[543,707,1811,1838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" pagination="687 - 698" refId="ref5213" refString="Li, G., Wan, X. Q., Batten, D. J., Bengtson, P., Xi, D. P. &amp; Wang, P. J. (2009) Spinicaudatans from the Upper Cretaceous Nenjiang Formation of the Songliao Basin, northeast China: taxonomy and biostratigraphy. Cretaceous Research, 30 (3), 687 - 698. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2008.12.008" type="journal article" year="2009">
Li 
<emphasis box="[576,625,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="158">et al</emphasis>
